been studied together.

00:12:01.990 --> 00:12:05.760
My story centers on two preachers.

00:12:05.760 --> 00:12:10.810
Church men are not the only, or
even the only important actors

00:12:10.810 --> 00:12:13.810
in the story, but through
their sermons, lectures,

00:12:13.810 --> 00:12:19.170
and journals we can learn about the
common folks who's traces otherwise

00:12:19.170 --> 00:12:22.310
don't appear in the
historical record.

00:12:22.310 --> 00:12:26.760
First is this guy, who I described
on the way up as an upstart Brit.

00:12:26.760 --> 00:12:29.980
The cherubic little
man, Thomas Coke,

00:12:29.980 --> 00:12:35.110
who was born into a prosperous
English family in 1747,

00:12:35.110 --> 00:12:38.160
educated at Oxford, and
ordained as a Priest

00:12:38.160 --> 00:12:41.390
in the Church of England in 1770.

00:12:41.390 --> 00:12:46.240
He came under the influence of
John Wesley's evangelical Methodism

00:12:46.240 --> 00:12:51.590
in 1776 and Coke began
preaching in fields,

00:12:51.590 --> 00:12:57.320
a good sign in North America,
a very bad sign in Britain.

00:12:57.320 --> 00:13:01.120
Influential parishioners
at his church objected.

00:13:01.120 --> 00:13:04.260
A new Priest was secretly hired.

00:13:04.260 --> 00:13:08.630
Coke was suddenly dismissed
while standing up to preach

00:13:08.630 --> 00:13:14.110
on Easter Sunday 1777, and
he was wrung out of church

00:13:14.110 --> 00:13:17.010
like being drummed
out of the military.

00:13:17.010 --> 00:13:22.040
He strode down the center aisle as
the bells pealed and was greeted

00:13:22.040 --> 00:13:28.460
by a mob outside who were already
drunk on cider but he rebounded.

00:13:28.460 --> 00:13:33.420
He became John Wesley's confidante,
drafted much of his correspondence,

00:13:33.420 --> 00:13:37.290
and all the Methodist
petitions to Parliament.

00:13:37.290 --> 00:13:43.290
In September 1784, Wesley
ordained Coke as a Bishop

00:13:43.290 --> 00:13:47.630
for the rapidly growing
American branch of the movement.

00:13:47.630 --> 00:13:52.320
Coke left quickly for America
when his fellow clergy accused him

00:13:52.320 --> 00:13:57.360
of exercising undue influence
over a senile Wesley.

00:13:57.360 --> 00:14:02.940
In December 1784, he arrived
in America and began the work

00:14:02.940 --> 00:14:09.060
of organizing a new, separate
Methodist church here.

00:14:09.060 --> 00:14:14.510
In early 1785, Coke
drafted new rules

00:14:14.510 --> 00:14:17.280
for the church in a
book of discipline.

00:14:17.280 --> 00:14:21.500
Coke's rules were designed
to eradicate slavery.

00:14:21.500 --> 00:14:26.720
He included provisions that copied
Virginia's Manumission statue

00:14:26.720 --> 00:14:30.600
that allowed masters to free
slaves in the Commonwealth.

00:14:30.600 --> 00:14:36.970
That statute had been enacted
in 1782, and by early 1785,

00:14:36.970 --> 00:14:41.550
had produced Manumissions
but also dedicated opposition

00:14:41.550 --> 00:14:44.410
from a pro-slavery majority.

00:14:44.410 --> 00:14:47.450
Coke took Manumission
a step further.

00:14:47.450 --> 00:14:51.530
He required that all church
members manumit their slaves

00:14:51.530 --> 00:14:57.840
within two years or be denied
communion and eventually expelled.

00:14:57.840 --> 00:15:01.400
After the church was formed
and its discipline written,

00:15:01.400 --> 00:15:04.510
Coke left on a preaching
tour of Virginia.

00:15:04.510 --> 00:15:07.720
From February to April 1785,

00:15:07.720 --> 00:15:12.640
he sermonized against the
unchristian act of slave holding.

00:15:12.640 --> 00:15:15.590
He reported in his
journal repeatedly

00:15:15.590 --> 00:15:19.080
that he was greeted by
outrage and violence.

00:15:19.080 --> 00:15:22.600
When he preached near Norfolk
and here I'm quoting from him,

00:15:22.600 --> 00:15:27.560
"A high headed lady offered 50
pounds to anyone who would give

00:15:27.560 --> 00:15:31.370
that little Englishman 100 lashes."

00:15:31.370 --> 00:15:36.520
At another house, Coke debated
slavery with a Colonel Bedford who,

00:15:36.520 --> 00:15:41.740 position:56%
"Used some threats" and as Coke's
reputation spread, doors were closed

00:15:41.740 --> 00:15:44.580
against him, he was
indicted for sedition

00:15:44.580 --> 00:15:49.680
and at least one plan was formed
to murder him but he left the state

00:15:49.680 --> 00:15:54.480
in May, before the law or the
assassins could catch up with him.

00:15:54.480 --> 00:15:59.370
But he left behind an
antislavery petition,

00:15:59.370 --> 00:16:02.770
which he gave to itinerant
Methodist evangelists

00:16:02.770 --> 00:16:04.460
to carry around Virginia.

00:16:04.460 --> 00:16:08.520
In the petition, Coke
called for the legislature

00:16:08.520 --> 00:16:12.830
to abolish the grand
abomination of slavery.

00:16:12.830 --> 00:16:17.650
He argued that slaveholders acted
against the most fundamental goal

00:16:17.650 --> 00:16:21.490
of Christianity, the
return of the Messiah.

00:16:21.490 --> 00:16:26.360
He said that enslavement made it
virtually impossible for a slave

00:16:26.360 --> 00:16:30.640
to receive the noble
principles of the Gospel meaning

00:16:30.640 --> 00:16:35.650
that slaveholders actively
prevented Christian progress.

00:16:35.650 --> 00:16:39.960
The boldness of Coke's claims
might well cause an uproar

00:16:39.960 --> 00:16:45.450
because he argued that anyone who
owned a slave was anti-Christian

00:16:45.450 --> 00:16:50.520
and the tone deaf Coke added
another insult, a political one.

00:16:50.520 --> 00:16:53.730
As an Englishman, he should
have known that his opinions

00:16:53.730 --> 00:16:58.990
on the American Revolution might
not be well received in Virginia.

00:16:58.990 --> 00:17:02.780
None the less, his petition
claimed that, and here I'm quoting,

00:17:02.780 --> 00:17:04.220
"The oppression exercised

00:17:04.220 --> 00:17:08.450
over slaves exceeds the
oppression formerly exercised

00:17:08.450 --> 00:17:12.180 position:56%
over these states by Great Britain."

00:17:12.180 --> 00:17:15.910
These were fighting
words and William Graham,

00:17:15.910 --> 00:17:18.780
our second preacher,
picked up the gauntlet.

00:17:18.780 --> 00:17:23.770
Graham was born in 1746,
in Paxton, Pennsylvania.

00:17:23.770 --> 00:17:28.600
His family were Scott's Irish
covenanters, that is Presbyterians

00:17:28.600 --> 00:17:32.460
who still remembered the
brutal British suppression

00:17:32.460 --> 00:17:35.530
of the Scottish rebellion
in the 17th century.

00:17:35.530 --> 00:17:39.730
Graham hated the British and
maintained a lifelong sympathy

00:17:39.730 --> 00:17:42.950
for populist vigilante movements.

00:17:42.950 --> 00:17:47.270
In many senses, this guy
Graham was Coke's opposite.

00:17:47.270 --> 00:17:52.150
He was hatchet faced and
lanky, not a gifted speaker.

00:17:52.150 --> 00:17:57.570
His sermons were monotonous and
he was a strict disciplinarian.

00:17:57.570 --> 00:18:03.490 position:56%
His congregations tended to be small
but he excelled as a schoolmaster,

00:18:03.490 --> 00:18:08.220
where his discipline was
imposed on less powerful objects.

00:18:08.220 --> 00:18:13.810
The school he founded was first
known as the Liberty Hall Academy

00:18:13.810 --> 00:18:17.290
and now Washington
and Lee University.

00:18:17.290 --> 00:18:22.850 position:56%
It was successful, but it never
made him much money, which brings us

00:18:22.850 --> 00:18:27.010
to my next point, the
question of minister's salaries

00:18:27.010 --> 00:18:32.090
and how the debate over tax support
for preachers eventually blended

00:18:32.090 --> 00:18:35.440
in to the backlash
against Thomas Coke.

00:18:35.440 --> 00:18:41.060
In December 1784, Patrick
Henry proposed a bill

00:18:41.060 --> 00:18:45.940
that would require each taxpayer
to designate a portion of his taxes

00:18:45.940 --> 00:18:49.080
to a Christian minister
of his choice.

00:18:49.080 --> 00:18:53.590
This general assessment bill, as it
was called, seemed like a good idea

00:18:53.590 --> 00:18:57.680 position:56%
to Henry and others, who worried
about a decline in church attendance

00:18:57.680 --> 00:19:02.000 position:56%
and the closing of schools
maintained by the established Church

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:05.930
of England clergy, many of whose
churches had been looted during the

00:19:05.930 --> 00:19:12.020
revolution and whose tax support
had been suspended since 1776.

00:19:12.020 --> 00:19:17.650
By 1784, the church
was in free fall.

00:19:17.650 --> 00:19:22.060
Presbyterians were
actually sympathetic.

00:19:22.060 --> 00:19:26.290
Graham often wrote petitions to the
Virginia General Assembly on behalf

00:19:26.290 --> 00:19:30.520
of the church and now he
co-authored an endorsement

00:19:30.520 --> 00:19:32.820
of the assessment bill.

00:19:32.820 --> 00:19:37.670
Graham had been dismayed by
enlightenment deism which I'm sorry

00:19:37.670 --> 00:19:40.810
to tell you Ted, he
called the French Principle

00:19:40.810 --> 00:19:45.960
but equally important, Graham's
income had suffered terribly during

00:19:45.960 --> 00:19:50.000
the revolution even though
he was an ardent patriot.

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:53.990
He was so patriotic that one
Sunday sermon he used to call

00:19:53.990 --> 00:19:58.080
for volunteers to fight
against the British and he wound

00:19:58.080 --> 00:20:02.090
up keying himself up so
much he volunteered himself.

00:20:02.090 --> 00:20:06.860
He never saw action but he boasted
of his service to the revolution

00:20:06.860 --> 00:20:08.890
for the rest of his life.

00:20:08.890 --> 00:20:12.800
Yet, the conflict impoverished him
because all his students went off

00:20:12.800 --> 00:20:17.880
to fight and the end of the war
only brought a deep recession.

00:20:17.880 --> 00:20:22.520
Patrick Henry's general assessment
bill gave him the prospect

00:20:22.520 --> 00:20:28.570
of a steady income but Graham soon
learned that the Presbytian laity,

00:20:28.570 --> 00:20:33.000
his congregants, would not
stand for a general assessment.

00:20:33.000 --> 00:20:36.510
They had been used to controlling
the salaries of ministers

00:20:36.510 --> 00:20:43.360
and they objected that Henry's bill
would free clergy from lay control.

00:20:43.360 --> 00:20:46.620
Graham was not known to
back away from a fight,

00:20:46.620 --> 00:20:50.100
he was quite a pugilist, and he
might well have stood his ground

00:20:50.100 --> 00:20:55.090
on the general assessment bill
but slavery entered the picture.

00:20:55.090 --> 00:20:57.280
Coke appeared on the scene just

00:20:57.280 --> 00:21:01.050
after Graham's pro-assessment
petition was submitted.

00:21:01.050 --> 00:21:06.020
Coke of course, was British,
elite, arrogant, plump,

00:21:06.020 --> 00:21:08.890 position:56%
tailor-made to be Graham's chew toy.

00:21:08.890 --> 00:21:13.800
The threat to slavey from
Coke affected Graham directly.

00:21:13.800 --> 00:21:18.330
He owned six slaves, according
to the census of 1790,

00:21:18.330 --> 00:21:22.350
and his school Liberty
Hall also owned slaves.

00:21:22.350 --> 00:21:27.190
By the mid-spring of 1785, in
other words coinciding exactly

00:21:27.190 --> 00:21:30.930
with Coke's tour, it sounds
so funny Coke's tour right,

00:21:30.930 --> 00:21:34.720
because there's a [inaudible]
but it's a different Coke.

00:21:34.720 --> 00:21:40.730
By the mid-spring of 1785, Graham's
about face on disestablishment was

00:21:40.730 --> 00:21:45.610
so complete that Presbyterians
selected him once again

00:21:45.610 --> 00:21:49.250
to draft a petition, this one,

00:21:49.250 --> 00:21:53.860
a full-throated call
for disestablishment.

00:21:53.860 --> 00:21:58.390 position:56%
Now, Graham argued that patriots had
fought against British oppression

00:21:58.390 --> 00:22:03.490
in spirituals as well as temporals,
that it was a religious war

00:22:03.490 --> 00:22:06.980
and that continued establishment
would be a fatal symbol

00:22:06.980 --> 00:22:10.350
of what he called abject slavery.

00:22:10.350 --> 00:22:13.250
For the first time, a
religious organization,

00:22:13.250 --> 00:22:16.990
the Presbyterian Church,
directly called for passage

00:22:16.990 --> 00:22:21.550
of Thomas Jefferson's bill for
establishing religious freedom,

00:22:21.550 --> 00:22:24.270
which had been kicking
around the legislature

00:22:24.270 --> 00:22:27.250
for years without much support.

00:22:27.250 --> 00:22:32.120
All of a sudden, in
1785, popular support

00:22:32.120 --> 00:22:35.710
for disestablishment took off.

00:22:35.710 --> 00:22:39.250
The traditional explanation
(gesture to Ted) is

00:22:39.250 --> 00:22:45.130 position:56%
that smart Parliamentary maneuvering
by James Madison deserves credit

00:22:45.130 --> 00:22:48.220
but I want us to think about
another side of the story,

00:22:48.220 --> 00:22:53.630
the missing link is Thomas
Coke's anti-slavery campaign,

00:22:53.630 --> 00:23:00.650
which convinced Graham and others
of a link between pro-slavery

00:23:00.650 --> 00:23:05.210
and pro-disestablishment or
anti-slavery and pro-establishment,

00:23:05.210 --> 00:23:08.640 position:56%
they're flip sides of the same coin.

00:23:08.640 --> 00:23:11.660
Graham explained how
separation of church

00:23:11.660 --> 00:23:14.820
and state would protect slavery.

00:23:14.820 --> 00:23:19.830
He also became the first clergyman
and the first academic leader

00:23:19.830 --> 00:23:24.180
to speak out in favor
of slavery and he did

00:23:24.180 --> 00:23:27.730
so clearly in response to Coke.

00:23:27.730 --> 00:23:31.360
In a lecture that Graham
gave at Liberty Hall starting

00:23:31.360 --> 00:23:37.940
in the mid-1780s, he explained why
Virginia must embrace both slavery

00:23:37.940 --> 00:23:42.900
and disestablishment and how
each reinforced the other.

00:23:42.900 --> 00:23:48.180
Not only had the revolution been
fought to secure slavery he said,

00:23:48.180 --> 00:23:52.700
but now a tool of the British
administration meaning our pale

00:23:52.700 --> 00:23:58.570
Coke, had undertaken to reverse the
American victory, hiding his plot

00:23:58.570 --> 00:24:03.630
to destroy the country
behind the veil of piety.

00:24:03.630 --> 00:24:07.900
Graham answered Coke in an
equally religious register.

00:24:07.900 --> 00:24:13.170 position:56%
The word of God, Graham said,
directly contradicted the Methodists

00:24:13.170 --> 00:24:16.680
and as Coke's petition was
carried around the Commonwealth

00:24:16.680 --> 00:24:22.590 position:56%
by Methodist itinerants, Graham and
pro-slavery petitions outpaced them,

00:24:22.590 --> 00:24:35.050
drawing many hundreds, about
1,500 evangelical signatures

00:24:35.050 --> 00:24:42.150
and dwarfing the few dozen
on the anti-slavery petition.

00:24:42.150 --> 00:24:46.200
The pro-slavery petitions track
Graham's lecture almost word

00:24:46.200 --> 00:24:47.500
for word.

00:24:47.500 --> 00:24:51.140
The central argument was that
Christian scripture did not

00:24:51.140 --> 00:24:54.700
in any sense condemn
slavery and that any attempt

00:24:54.700 --> 00:24:58.120
to interpret either the
Old or New Testaments

00:24:58.120 --> 00:25:02.240
as anti-slavery would
pervert the word of God.

00:25:02.240 --> 00:25:07.060
Instead, scripture instructed that
religious status such as conversion

00:25:07.060 --> 00:25:13.820
to Christianity in no way altered
civil status such as enslavement.

00:25:13.820 --> 00:25:18.420
The liberty conferred by Christian
faith was an internal freedom

00:25:18.420 --> 00:25:21.720
from sin and the devil
rather than any change

00:25:21.720 --> 00:25:24.940 position:56%
in the believer's outward condition.

00:25:24.940 --> 00:25:27.750
Paul's First Letter to the
Corinthians established

00:25:27.750 --> 00:25:31.410
that even Christian
slaves were to remain loyal

00:25:31.410 --> 00:25:34.500
and obedient to their masters.

00:25:34.500 --> 00:25:39.280
Colonial statues had written
this into law as early as 1677.

00:25:39.280 --> 00:25:42.740
Conversion was not a
ticket to emancipation.

00:25:42.740 --> 00:25:48.770
In other words, spiritual freedom
and bodily coercion belonged

00:25:48.770 --> 00:25:53.850
to two distinct spheres, the
first inward and religious

00:25:53.850 --> 00:25:57.630
and the second outward
and political.

00:25:57.630 --> 00:26:00.910
These scriptural arguments
were made with new force

00:26:00.910 --> 00:26:02.620
to counter the Methodists,

00:26:02.620 --> 00:26:08.460 position:56%
who charged that bondage affected
the spiritual health of slaveholders

00:26:08.460 --> 00:26:12.070
and urged changes in the
secular law to save the souls

00:26:12.070 --> 00:26:15.000
of masters as well as slaves.

00:26:15.000 --> 00:26:19.820
The danger to slavery was apparent
and Graham and others realized

00:26:19.820 --> 00:26:25.210
that antislavery religion had
been let loose in Virginia.

00:26:25.210 --> 00:26:28.820
Under the general assessment
bill, just to give one example,

00:26:28.820 --> 00:26:33.100
tax dollars could well flow to
antislavery ministers either

00:26:33.100 --> 00:26:36.740
because the individual taxpayers
directed the funds to preachers

00:26:36.740 --> 00:26:41.860 position:56%
who opposed slavery or the ministers
who received tax funding acted

00:26:41.860 --> 00:26:45.230
at the behest of church
leaders like Coke.

00:26:45.230 --> 00:26:51.260
A religious establishment
therefore posed a danger.

00:26:51.260 --> 00:26:56.550
Separation of church and state in
Virginia was built on this distrust

00:26:56.550 --> 00:27:02.230
of clergy, who were not dependent
directly on local congregations,

00:27:02.230 --> 00:27:07.460 position:56%
set them free from their congregants
and who knows what would happen.

00:27:07.460 --> 00:27:10.850
Evidence for this overlap
in commitments to slavery

00:27:10.850 --> 00:27:14.510
and disestablishment is
found in the signatures

00:27:14.510 --> 00:27:16.920
on both sets of petitions.

00:27:16.920 --> 00:27:20.840
That is, pro-establishment
and proslavery.

00:27:20.840 --> 00:27:23.780
We can trace the political
actions of the laity

00:27:23.780 --> 00:27:26.570
through this unique resource.

00:27:26.570 --> 00:27:30.430
Five of the six counties
that memorialized in favor

00:27:30.430 --> 00:27:35.340
of slavery also sent
pro-disestablishment petitions.

00:27:35.340 --> 00:27:39.760
Common signatures are found in
about 40 percent of the total,

00:27:39.760 --> 00:27:44.760
a remarkable convergence of
religious and political activism.

00:27:44.760 --> 00:27:49.030
In his convergence, religious
conviction was painted as private

00:27:49.030 --> 00:27:55.180
and personal while enslavement
rested firmly on the political side

00:27:55.180 --> 00:27:58.460
that is, with the legislature.

00:27:58.460 --> 00:28:03.070
One might think of this
resolution as a kind of compromise,

00:28:03.070 --> 00:28:08.100
proslavery evangelicals apparently
believed they could buy peace

00:28:08.100 --> 00:28:11.460
by parking slavery in
the political realm.

00:28:11.460 --> 00:28:15.060
They told themselves that they
were neutral or apolitical

00:28:15.060 --> 00:28:19.160
on the question even as their
doctrine of the division

00:28:19.160 --> 00:28:23.110
between religion and politics
clearly protected a proslavery

00:28:23.110 --> 00:28:27.870
status quo and the system worked.

00:28:27.870 --> 00:28:32.570
It silenced antislavery voices
quickly and effectively.

00:28:32.570 --> 00:28:38.680
Thomas Coke conceded in 1787,
that it had been ill judged of him

00:28:38.680 --> 00:28:43.780
to preach antislavery from
the pulpit and in 1791,

00:28:43.780 --> 00:28:45.820
the Hanover Presbyterian
(we saw a picture

00:28:45.820 --> 00:28:48.000
of their beautiful church) decided

00:28:48.000 --> 00:28:51.780
that enslaved persons could be
married in the sight of God,

00:28:51.780 --> 00:28:55.840
even though the civil law would
not recognize their relationship.

00:28:55.840 --> 00:28:59.620
But if one of the spouses
was sold away from the other,

00:28:59.620 --> 00:29:04.740
then the marriage was dissolved
as if the other was dead.

00:29:04.740 --> 00:29:09.150
Baptists also endorses a death
or removal standard saying

00:29:09.150 --> 00:29:13.260
that any other policy might
yield unpleasant things.

00:29:13.260 --> 00:29:17.630
Such marriages were a
potentially enormous issue.

00:29:17.630 --> 00:29:20.000
One study concluded
that one out of three

00:29:20.000 --> 00:29:22.890
of all slave marriages
was terminated

00:29:22.890 --> 00:29:26.870
by the internal slave
trade, that's a lot.

00:29:26.870 --> 00:29:30.840
Acceptance of the divide
between freedom of the spirit

00:29:30.840 --> 00:29:36.480 position:56%
and the physical coercion of slavery
also spread among the Methodists.

00:29:36.480 --> 00:29:39.600
By the mid-1790s, they
had backed away

00:29:39.600 --> 00:29:42.790
from their emancipatory
rules saying now

00:29:42.790 --> 00:29:46.360
that they hoped Christian faith
would sweeten the bitter cup

00:29:46.360 --> 00:29:47.930
of bondage.

00:29:47.930 --> 00:29:52.730
Some white evangelicals objected
including one Methodist minister

00:29:52.730 --> 00:29:58.100
in the 1790s who said that human
laws could not wash away the guilt

00:29:58.100 --> 00:30:00.110
of an act prohibited
by the word of God.

00:30:00.110 --> 00:30:06.910
But his son, also a Methodist
minister, became a slaveholder.

00:30:06.910 --> 00:30:12.390
So where does this story of
freedom and coercion leave us?

00:30:12.390 --> 00:30:15.160
It's a different picture
of disestablishment,

00:30:15.160 --> 00:30:18.410
maybe a little less heroic
but believable in light

00:30:18.410 --> 00:30:22.460
of religious history and
political reality and of course,

00:30:22.460 --> 00:30:24.210
there's the question of Jefferson.

00:30:24.210 --> 00:30:25.510
What did he think?

00:30:25.510 --> 00:30:28.690
He was out of the country in 1785,

00:30:28.690 --> 00:30:31.880
but he also followed
the debate closely.

00:30:31.880 --> 00:30:35.990
Did he accept the divide
between freedom and coercion?

00:30:35.990 --> 00:30:38.870 position:56%
It looks like he did 20 years later.

00:30:38.870 --> 00:30:45.710
A clue from 1815 is found in a
letter he wrote to a correspondent

00:30:45.710 --> 00:30:47.810
who had sent him a book of sermons

00:30:47.810 --> 00:30:51.180
by the Reverend Alexander
MacLeod of New York.

00:30:51.180 --> 00:30:53.840
MacLeod called for
preaching on politics,

00:30:53.840 --> 00:30:56.710 position:56%
especially in opposition to slavery.

00:30:56.710 --> 00:31:00.890
In his letter, Jefferson thanked
his correspondent for the book

00:31:00.890 --> 00:31:04.350
but then said that MacLeod
had breached the contract

00:31:04.350 --> 00:31:06.340
that underlay religious freedom

00:31:06.340 --> 00:31:10.250
by discussing public
affairs in the pulpit.

00:31:10.250 --> 00:31:14.870
He advised ministers to avoid
such topics as the construction

00:31:14.870 --> 00:31:18.180
of government or the
characters or conduct

00:31:18.180 --> 00:31:21.440 position:56%
of those administering it otherwise,

00:31:21.440 --> 00:31:24.750
they would violate the
terms of disestablishment.

00:31:24.750 --> 00:31:30.810
We're seeing a similar debate
today right, flipping that.

00:31:30.810 --> 00:31:35.210
But despite Virginia's outsized
importance in the early republic,

00:31:35.210 --> 00:31:39.950 position:56%
it didn't actually control how other
jurisdictions interpreted their

00:31:39.950 --> 00:31:41.580
own law.

00:31:41.580 --> 00:31:45.140
The Virginia model, as it was
called in the 19th century,

00:31:45.140 --> 00:31:49.600
never governed separation of
church and state as perfectly

00:31:49.600 --> 00:31:51.600
as Virginia's secular thinkers

00:31:51.600 --> 00:31:55.170
and proslavery Christians
hoped it would.

00:31:55.170 --> 00:32:00.370
Instead, the mandate to
consign concerns about slavery

00:32:00.370 --> 00:32:05.460
to the political sphere began
to create its own politics.

00:32:05.460 --> 00:32:10.270
Those who could not stand the
constraint often left and many

00:32:10.270 --> 00:32:13.540
who had no other choice
were sold away.

00:32:13.540 --> 00:32:16.770
Some found their way
to freedom and those

00:32:16.770 --> 00:32:20.790
who had left voluntarily
still resented the strictures.

00:32:20.790 --> 00:32:23.930
Over time, the strict
divide between religion

00:32:23.930 --> 00:32:28.580
and slavery began to
work its own undoing.

00:32:28.580 --> 00:32:33.610
The end of that story is beyond the
scope of my talk today but one way

00:32:33.610 --> 00:32:36.760
to summarize the trajectory
is to note that the first wall

00:32:36.760 --> 00:32:39.840
of separation was all about power,

00:32:39.840 --> 00:32:43.490
but it wound up not
being all powerful.

00:32:43.490 --> 00:32:45.290
Thank you.

00:32:45.290 --> 00:33:00.270
[ Applause ]

00:33:00.270 --> 00:33:04.560
&gt;&gt; Thank you Sally, that
was somewhat mind blowing

00:33:04.560 --> 00:33:07.440
and thank you Ted, for
the earlier introduction.

00:33:07.440 --> 00:33:11.960
It's wonderful to be here with you.

00:33:11.960 --> 00:33:14.710
My name is Peter Manseau.

00:33:14.710 --> 00:33:17.970
I work down the road at the
National Museum of American History

00:33:17.970 --> 00:33:20.640
where I'm the Curator of
American Religious History

00:33:20.640 --> 00:33:23.910
and this is my first time
speaking in a building

00:33:23.910 --> 00:33:25.460
where I've done quite
a lot of research

00:33:25.460 --> 00:33:28.510
so it's truly an honor to be here.

00:33:28.510 --> 00:33:30.950
I would like to speak with
you a bit today about religion

00:33:30.950 --> 00:33:35.950
in America before the
Civil War and one way

00:33:35.950 --> 00:33:39.070
in which the subject is often
addressed has a lot of resonance

00:33:39.070 --> 00:33:44.440
with Sally's talk, it
often is explored as a way

00:33:44.440 --> 00:33:47.640
of exploring the tensions
among Christians

00:33:47.640 --> 00:33:50.170
about the place of
slavery in scripture.

00:33:50.170 --> 00:33:53.840
How was it that some religious
people saw it as an abomination

00:33:53.840 --> 00:33:57.030
like our Reverend Coke we just
heard about, while others argued

00:33:57.030 --> 00:34:00.280
as Texas did in its
causes for secession

00:34:00.280 --> 00:34:04.270
that African servitude was
authorized and revealed

00:34:04.270 --> 00:34:08.120
by the revered will of
the almighty creator?

00:34:08.120 --> 00:34:10.610
Well, that religion can be
used to argue both sides

00:34:10.610 --> 00:34:14.350
of an issue will not be a surprise
to anyone here today I imagine

00:34:14.350 --> 00:34:18.280 position:56%
and so instead of pursing that
dimension, I'd like instead to focus

00:34:18.280 --> 00:34:21.640
on a lesser known aspect of
religion in America in the middle

00:34:21.640 --> 00:34:25.430
of the 19th century and that
is the struggle and endurance

00:34:25.430 --> 00:34:29.560
of forgotten forms of
American religious diversity.

00:34:29.560 --> 00:34:31.680
The landscape of American
religious difference

00:34:31.680 --> 00:34:35.600
in the US changed dramatically
in the 1860s.

00:34:35.600 --> 00:34:39.500
Some of this had to do with the
war and some of it simply had to do

00:34:39.500 --> 00:34:43.640
with the ways in which the lines
between religious traditions tend

00:34:43.640 --> 00:34:50.800
to blur over time yet before
I get there to my main topic,

00:34:50.800 --> 00:34:54.320 position:56%
since this is my first time
speaking in the Library of Congress,

00:34:54.320 --> 00:34:57.390
I can't resist telling you
one of my favorite stories

00:34:57.390 --> 00:35:01.510
about a disagreement
concerning religious differences

00:35:01.510 --> 00:35:02.980
in American history.

00:35:02.980 --> 00:35:05.690
It's a story that actually
has to do with the founding

00:35:05.690 --> 00:35:07.490
of this great institution.

00:35:07.490 --> 00:35:11.880
As many of you will likely
know and as I heard someone,

00:35:11.880 --> 00:35:16.720
a tour guide giving a tour about
this just as I was walking in,

00:35:16.720 --> 00:35:19.420
the founding collection of
the Library of Congress came

00:35:19.420 --> 00:35:25.120
from Monticello to Washington 202
years ago this spring in the form

00:35:25.120 --> 00:35:30.360
of 6,487 books that
Thomas Jefferson had sold

00:35:30.360 --> 00:35:34.890
to the federal government near
the end of the War of 1812.

00:35:34.890 --> 00:35:37.690
Congress had a reference
collection before that of course,

00:35:37.690 --> 00:35:40.100
but it was a little
less than half the size

00:35:40.100 --> 00:35:43.340
and those 3,000 books
had gone up in smoke

00:35:43.340 --> 00:35:47.950
when the British burned
Washington in August of 1814.

00:35:47.950 --> 00:35:51.440
Jefferson had been retired
for five years by then

00:35:51.440 --> 00:35:54.760
and so he didn't get a briefing
on the fact that the White House,

00:35:54.760 --> 00:35:57.670
the Capitol and other
federal buildings had been all

00:35:57.670 --> 00:35:58.970
but destroyed.

00:35:58.970 --> 00:36:02.990 position:56%
Instead, he learned about it as many
of us might have, he read about it

00:36:02.990 --> 00:36:07.540
in the newspaper and apparently
one of the first things he thought

00:36:07.540 --> 00:36:11.230
about when he learned of the
destruction were all those books

00:36:11.230 --> 00:36:16.060
in the Capitol, all that
paper that fueled the fire.

00:36:16.060 --> 00:36:19.300
Wondering what he might do
about it and perhaps considering

00:36:19.300 --> 00:36:22.780
if this sad turn of events
might also free up some space

00:36:22.780 --> 00:36:26.130
in his own over-burdened
bookshelves, Jefferson wrote

00:36:26.130 --> 00:36:28.440
to a friend on the
Congressional Library Committee

00:36:28.440 --> 00:36:32.440
and he basically said, so I
hear you might need some books.

00:36:32.440 --> 00:36:37.580
What he actually wrote was this,
"I learned from the newspapers

00:36:37.580 --> 00:36:42.370 position:56%
that the vandalism of our enemy has
triumphed at Washington over science

00:36:42.370 --> 00:36:46.260
as well as the arts by the
destruction of the public library

00:36:46.260 --> 00:36:49.480
with a noble edifice in
which it was deposited.

00:36:49.480 --> 00:36:52.400
I presume it will be among the
earliest objects of Congress

00:36:52.400 --> 00:36:55.740
to re-commence their collection."

00:36:55.740 --> 00:36:58.130
Jefferson was beating
around the bush a bit here.

00:36:58.130 --> 00:37:01.840
He was clearing his throat before
making Congress an offer he hoped

00:37:01.840 --> 00:37:03.140
they could not refuse.

00:37:03.140 --> 00:37:07.090
As he then explained,
like a true salesman,

00:37:07.090 --> 00:37:10.940
the books he had available
were the best in the land.

00:37:10.940 --> 00:37:14.250
They were the best because
only he had had the resources

00:37:14.250 --> 00:37:17.790
and the time throughout his
life to do the kind of research

00:37:17.790 --> 00:37:22.620
and travel necessary to acquire
a significant collection.

00:37:22.620 --> 00:37:26.000
He proudly noted that he had spent
much of his time as US Minister

00:37:26.000 --> 00:37:29.100
to France shopping for books.

00:37:29.100 --> 00:37:33.360
While residing in Paris, he
said, he devoted every afternoon

00:37:33.360 --> 00:37:37.880
to examining all the principle
bookstores, turning over every book

00:37:37.880 --> 00:37:43.310
with his own hands, apparently
unconcerned if anyone would wonder

00:37:43.310 --> 00:37:46.890
if he was also doing his job,
Jefferson sent this letter off

00:37:46.890 --> 00:37:53.440
to Washington and those 6,487
books soon followed on 10 wagons

00:37:53.440 --> 00:37:58.610
that traveled more than
100 miles over bumpy roads.

00:37:58.610 --> 00:38:01.010
But their journey from
that Virginia hilltop

00:38:01.010 --> 00:38:04.230 position:56%
to Capitol Hill was far from simple.

00:38:04.230 --> 00:38:08.390 position:56%
In between Jefferson's letter in the
fall and the loading of the wagons

00:38:08.390 --> 00:38:13.810
in the spring, his books became
the focus of a remarkable debate.

00:38:13.810 --> 00:38:17.850
It raged in the press and
in Congress for months.

00:38:17.850 --> 00:38:22.600 position:56%
It's subject was the possibly
atheistical character of the library

00:38:22.600 --> 00:38:25.430
and of the man who had acquired it.

00:38:25.430 --> 00:38:30.410
It was said that Jefferson's
books were full of infidel ideas,

00:38:30.410 --> 00:38:33.720
ideas that might infect the
nation if they were allowed

00:38:33.720 --> 00:38:36.360
into the halls of government.

00:38:36.360 --> 00:38:40.490
With the smoke of British arson
still lingering over Washington,

00:38:40.490 --> 00:38:44.570
some members of Congress even
discussed burning the offending

00:38:44.570 --> 00:38:46.640
titles in Jefferson's library

00:38:46.640 --> 00:38:49.900
to avoid potential
spiritual contamination.

00:38:49.900 --> 00:38:53.590
This campaign was led by a
federalist representative

00:38:53.590 --> 00:38:58.110 position:56%
from my home state of Massachusetts,
Representative Cyrus King,

00:38:58.110 --> 00:39:03.170 position:56%
who argued that evidence Jefferson's
collection contained "Many books

00:39:03.170 --> 00:39:07.130
of irreligious and immoral
tendency could be found not only

00:39:07.130 --> 00:39:10.320
in the character of the man who's
assembled it, but in the fact

00:39:10.320 --> 00:39:13.140
that he had done so in France."

00:39:14.440 --> 00:39:18.730
Other congressmen found King's talk
of book burning too much to take.

00:39:18.730 --> 00:39:22.190
Representative James Fiske of
Vermont, a democratic republican

00:39:22.190 --> 00:39:25.710
like Jefferson, reminded his
colleagues that King came

00:39:25.710 --> 00:39:29.540
from a state once known for hanging
witches and he wondered whether

00:39:29.540 --> 00:39:33.150 position:56%
that practice might be reintroduced.

00:39:33.150 --> 00:39:36.040
Maryland's Representative
Robert Wright asked King

00:39:36.040 --> 00:39:38.160
if he wanted to start
an inquisition.

00:39:38.160 --> 00:39:42.560
To this charge, King replied
that he had no such intention,

00:39:42.560 --> 00:39:46.020
at least not while his
party was in the minority.

00:39:46.020 --> 00:39:50.320
In the end, party politics
ruled the day.

00:39:50.320 --> 00:39:54.230
By a slim margin, the democratic
republican majority approved

00:39:54.230 --> 00:39:56.090
the purchase.

00:39:56.090 --> 00:39:59.040
Now, I mentioned this story
first of all as a reminder

00:39:59.040 --> 00:40:01.280
that Americans have been struggling

00:40:01.280 --> 00:40:04.120
with overheated rhetoric
surrounding religious difference

00:40:04.120 --> 00:40:09.130
for a very long time and maybe
we should count ourselves lucky

00:40:09.130 --> 00:40:10.900
that we don't hear much talk

00:40:10.900 --> 00:40:14.310
of hanging witches or
burning books lately.

00:40:14.310 --> 00:40:15.610
Not lately.

00:40:15.610 --> 00:40:19.920
Yet the truly fascinating thing
to me about this moment is this,

00:40:19.920 --> 00:40:23.500
while in Washington, Jefferson's
tastes seemed eclectic to the point

00:40:23.500 --> 00:40:27.630
of being threatening, in fact
they barely scratched the surface

00:40:27.630 --> 00:40:32.440
of the actual religious diversity
that existed beyond the Capitol.

00:40:32.440 --> 00:40:36.660
While government was arguing over
religious ideas, it was oblivious

00:40:36.660 --> 00:40:41.110
to many forms of religious
practice then found in the US.

00:40:41.110 --> 00:40:44.780
For example, among the
best known books included

00:40:44.780 --> 00:40:47.940 position:56%
in that original Jefferson
collection which came to the Library

00:40:47.940 --> 00:40:56.960
of Congress was this one,
Jefferson's 1734 edition

00:40:56.960 --> 00:41:01.320
of the Koran, which remains
here in the library today.

00:41:01.320 --> 00:41:05.320
Now, Jefferson's Koran is often
put forward as a symbol of some

00:41:05.320 --> 00:41:08.590
of the founding generations
curiosity about a variety

00:41:08.590 --> 00:41:11.830
of religious perspectives and
on the one hand it's appropriate

00:41:11.830 --> 00:41:13.130
to see it that way.

00:41:13.130 --> 00:41:16.160
Jefferson bought the book while
he was a young man studying law

00:41:16.160 --> 00:41:19.350
and he may have read it as
a way to make himself aware

00:41:19.350 --> 00:41:24.010
of Islam's influence on some
of the world's legal systems.

00:41:24.010 --> 00:41:29.020
Yet, viewing Jefferson's Koran
only as an American engagement

00:41:29.020 --> 00:41:35.630
with far off exotic beliefs
obscures a crucial fact.

00:41:35.630 --> 00:41:39.620
To many people living then
in Jefferson's young nation,

00:41:39.620 --> 00:41:42.960
this book meant very much more.

00:41:42.960 --> 00:41:48.970
As Jefferson's library rolled
north and his Koran went with it,

00:41:48.970 --> 00:41:56.370
this man was a 45-year-old resident
of Fayetteville, North Carolina.

00:41:56.370 --> 00:41:57.670
His name is Omar ibn Said.

00:41:57.670 --> 00:42:03.650
In 1815, he had been in this
country just eight years,

00:42:03.650 --> 00:42:06.660
all of them under the yoke of
a master he called a cruel man

00:42:06.660 --> 00:42:08.860 position:56%
and a kefyr, which means an infidel.

00:42:08.860 --> 00:42:14.380
After he was recaptured following
an attempt to escape from slavery,

00:42:14.380 --> 00:42:17.010
Omar ibn Said was locked
inside the County Jail

00:42:17.010 --> 00:42:19.970
in Cumberland County,
North Carolina.

00:42:19.970 --> 00:42:21.930
By this point, it was
no longer legal

00:42:21.930 --> 00:42:25.880 position:56%
to directly import human beings from
Africa and so for many residents

00:42:25.880 --> 00:42:29.730
of Fayetteville, it may have been
unusual to see a man who maintained

00:42:29.730 --> 00:42:32.350
so many of the traditions of
the land where he was born.

00:42:32.350 --> 00:42:37.810 position:56%
Now, while locked in his jail cell
in Fayetteville, Omar ibn Said began

00:42:37.810 --> 00:42:43.440
to draw a crowd first for his quiet
and some said mysterious demeanor,

00:42:43.440 --> 00:42:48.840 position:56%
then for the strange way in which he
prayed five times a day and finally,

00:42:48.840 --> 00:42:53.980
for the graffiti that he began
to put on his jail cell walls.

00:42:53.980 --> 00:42:57.250
Apparently, he had found some
coals from a warming fire

00:42:57.250 --> 00:43:00.300
that were large enough to
write with and he began

00:43:00.300 --> 00:43:03.850
to fill his jail cell
walls with Arabic script,

00:43:03.850 --> 00:43:06.550
most likely it was
verses from the Koran.

00:43:06.550 --> 00:43:09.540
As his story became known,

00:43:09.540 --> 00:43:12.400
it emerged that he had once
been a religious teacher.

00:43:12.400 --> 00:43:17.710 position:56%
He had been 37 years old when he was
captured in what was now Senegal.

00:43:17.710 --> 00:43:21.550
After his time in jail, Omar
ibn Said became the property

00:43:21.550 --> 00:43:25.070
of a prominent local political
family, which encouraged him

00:43:25.070 --> 00:43:28.490
to convert to Christianity
and soon persuaded him

00:43:28.490 --> 00:43:31.310
to write an account of his life.

00:43:31.310 --> 00:43:34.640
Through the decades that followed,
this family was successful

00:43:34.640 --> 00:43:39.260
in publicizing their successful
conversion of their enslaved man

00:43:39.260 --> 00:43:42.420
and they placed articles about
him throughout the United States.

00:43:42.420 --> 00:43:47.480
In 1825, a Philadelphia Christian
paper told the story of his time

00:43:47.480 --> 00:43:51.300 position:56%
in jail, which recounted his filling
the walls with Arabic graffiti

00:43:51.300 --> 00:43:54.430
and it also relayed how he had
been brought to his new faith.

00:43:54.430 --> 00:44:00.880
In 1837, an article in the Boston
Reporter hailed him as a convert

00:44:00.880 --> 00:44:04.930
from Mohammedism and it
devoted two full columns

00:44:04.930 --> 00:44:06.980
to his Christian virtues.

00:44:06.980 --> 00:44:11.740
In 1854, a reporter
wrote that he had,

00:44:11.740 --> 00:44:15.230
"Thrown aside the blood
stained Koran and now worships

00:44:15.230 --> 00:44:18.180 position:56%
at the feet of the Prince of Peace."

00:44:18.180 --> 00:44:22.290
In all of this, it was claimed
that though he was still enslaved,

00:44:22.290 --> 00:44:27.120
he wore no bonds but those
of gratitude and affection.

00:44:27.120 --> 00:44:33.970
Yet, a very different story was
told by Omar ibn Said himself.

00:44:36.210 --> 00:44:40.680
He originally wrote the account
of his experiences in Arabic,

00:44:40.680 --> 00:44:45.300
which those taking credit for his
conversion could not read very well

00:44:45.300 --> 00:44:49.360
and in fact, his original
account was not translated

00:44:49.360 --> 00:44:51.950
for a full I believe it's 17 years

00:44:51.950 --> 00:44:53.640
after he wrote his
account in Arabic.

00:44:53.640 --> 00:44:57.370
And if they had been able to
read his original account,

00:44:57.370 --> 00:45:01.800
they would have seen his adoption
of Christianity stated sincerely

00:45:01.800 --> 00:45:05.030
but also in very practical terms.

00:45:05.030 --> 00:45:11.040
"In freedom" he said, "He had
prayed as a Muslim but now,

00:45:11.040 --> 00:45:14.820
enslaved he would say
the Lord's Prayer."

00:45:14.820 --> 00:45:18.780
He also filled his text with
prophetic declarations directed

00:45:18.780 --> 00:45:21.860
at those who had enslaved him.

00:45:21.860 --> 00:45:27.270
"Oh people of America, oh people of
North Carolina," he wrote in 1831,

00:45:27.270 --> 00:45:30.830
"Do you have a good
generation that fears Allah?

00:45:30.830 --> 00:45:35.160
Are you confident that he who is
in heaven will not cause the earth

00:45:35.160 --> 00:45:37.740
to cave in beneath you
so that it will shake

00:45:37.740 --> 00:45:40.040
to pieces and overwhelm you?"

00:45:40.040 --> 00:45:46.430
Even after his conversion, Islam
continued to shape his experience

00:45:46.430 --> 00:45:50.380
of his enslavement and in
this, he was not alone.

00:45:50.380 --> 00:45:55.220
An estimated 20 percent of the
enslaved men and women brought

00:45:55.220 --> 00:45:57.640
to the Americas were Muslims.

00:45:57.640 --> 00:46:00.730
Some plantation owners made
it a point to add Muslims

00:46:00.730 --> 00:46:03.480
to their labor force,
relying on their experience

00:46:03.480 --> 00:46:06.390
with the cultivation
of indigo and rice.

00:46:06.390 --> 00:46:10.160
Muslim names and religious titles
appear in slave inventories

00:46:10.160 --> 00:46:13.540
and death records and all
of this, I should add,

00:46:13.540 --> 00:46:16.530
was fairly common knowledge
at the time.

00:46:16.530 --> 00:46:20.310
Every so often in the 18th
and 19th century press,

00:46:20.310 --> 00:46:24.200
other enslaved Muslims
became celebrities of a sort,

00:46:24.200 --> 00:46:26.620
most often because they
were discovered by white men

00:46:26.620 --> 00:46:29.460
who were struck by their erudition.

00:46:29.460 --> 00:46:34.240
The earliest known example of this
was a man who at the time was known

00:46:34.240 --> 00:46:37.740
as Job Ben Solomon and
he's now known more often

00:46:37.740 --> 00:46:43.870
as Ayuba Suleiman Diallo, who was
enslaved in Maryland in the 1730s.

00:46:43.870 --> 00:46:49.030 position:56%
After an escape attempt, he was like
Omar ibn Said, put in a jailhouse

00:46:49.030 --> 00:46:52.710
and there he met a local judge,
who was so taken with him

00:46:52.710 --> 00:46:55.620
that he wrote a book
about their encounter.

00:46:57.730 --> 00:47:03.750
This is the Memoirs of the Life of
Job 1734, by Judge Thomas Bluett.

00:47:03.750 --> 00:47:09.950
As the judge wrote, "He showed upon
all occasions a singular veneration

00:47:09.950 --> 00:47:13.440
for the name of God, and never
pronounced the word Allah

00:47:13.440 --> 00:47:17.360
without a peculiar accent and
a remarkable pause and indeed,

00:47:17.360 --> 00:47:21.030
his notions of God, providence,
and a future state were

00:47:21.030 --> 00:47:24.670
in the main very just
and reasonable."

00:47:24.670 --> 00:47:27.740
The most famous of these enslaved
Muslims who found their way

00:47:27.740 --> 00:47:31.390
into the American press
was probably this man,

00:47:31.390 --> 00:47:35.590
a man named Abdul-Rahman Ibrahim.

00:47:35.590 --> 00:47:42.520
In the press of the 1820s, he
was known as the Moorish Prince,

00:47:42.520 --> 00:47:45.150
and he came from an important
political family in his homeland

00:47:45.150 --> 00:47:47.350
of Timbuktu, now in Mali.

00:47:47.350 --> 00:47:50.030
His plight drew wide
attention in the 1820s,

00:47:50.030 --> 00:47:56.770
with newspaper stories
written around the country.

00:47:56.770 --> 00:47:59.890
Eventually, several well placed
supporters including Secretary

00:47:59.890 --> 00:48:03.750
of State Henry Clay and through
him, President John Quincy Adams,

00:48:03.750 --> 00:48:08.780
helped win his freedom and his
eventual relocation to Liberia.

00:48:08.780 --> 00:48:12.650
Now, before he left, he offered
a pointed critique of religion

00:48:12.650 --> 00:48:16.170
in the country in which he had
been enslaved for 40 years.

00:48:16.170 --> 00:48:19.410
As one newspaper account
noted, "He had read the Bible

00:48:19.410 --> 00:48:23.830
and admired its precepts but
added his principal objections are

00:48:23.830 --> 00:48:26.460 position:56%
that Christians do not follow them."

00:48:28.270 --> 00:48:31.050
The story of Islam in early
America is not merely one

00:48:31.050 --> 00:48:33.490
of isolated individuals however.

00:48:33.490 --> 00:48:36.520
Even being conservative in
counting their population,

00:48:36.520 --> 00:48:39.360
we're talking about tens
of thousands of people.

00:48:39.360 --> 00:48:42.390
To compare them to other
religious minorities at the time,

00:48:42.390 --> 00:48:46.670
we might consider that around 1800
there were some 40,000 Catholics,

00:48:46.670 --> 00:48:49.280
there were probably four
or five thousand Jews.

00:48:49.280 --> 00:48:51.740
It's entirely possible that
there were more individuals

00:48:51.740 --> 00:48:54.700
with a connection to Islam at
that point in American history

00:48:54.700 --> 00:48:57.360
than Catholics and Jews combined.

00:48:57.360 --> 00:49:01.860
Now, some of this community
tried to preserve the traditions

00:49:01.860 --> 00:49:05.120
in which they were raised in
hope of establishing communities

00:49:05.120 --> 00:49:07.530
with the same beliefs and practices

00:49:07.530 --> 00:49:10.710
that had sustained them
before enslavement.

00:49:10.710 --> 00:49:16.190 position:56%
Evidence of this can be seen in this
religious text, written in Arabic

00:49:16.190 --> 00:49:20.360 position:56%
in Georgia early in the 19th
century and if I'm permitted a plug,

00:49:20.360 --> 00:49:24.570
I should say that opening this
June at the National Museum

00:49:24.570 --> 00:49:26.400
of American History our exhibit,

00:49:26.400 --> 00:49:29.630
Religion in Early America will
feature this document along

00:49:29.630 --> 00:49:32.430
with the story of Omar ibn Said.

00:49:32.430 --> 00:49:36.490
The author of this document is
a man named Bilali Muhammad and,

00:49:36.490 --> 00:49:41.980 position:56%
like Omar ibn Said, he was born in
West Africa, most likely around 1770

00:49:41.980 --> 00:49:45.160
and he arrived in the
Americas in his 30s.

00:49:45.160 --> 00:49:48.210
He was purchased at Charleston,
South Carolina and brought

00:49:48.210 --> 00:49:52.700
to a cotton plantation on Sapelo
Island off the Georgia coast.

00:49:52.700 --> 00:49:57.010
Literate and multilingual,
Bilali rose to a trusted position

00:49:57.010 --> 00:50:00.810
on that island, even being
allowed to train other enslaved men

00:50:00.810 --> 00:50:05.940
with muskets for defense of the
island during the War of 1812.

00:50:05.940 --> 00:50:09.710
He seems also to have played a
role as a religious leader there.

00:50:09.710 --> 00:50:14.060
This 13 page document was once
thought to be simply his diary

00:50:14.060 --> 00:50:17.550
but recent scholarships suggest
that it actually outlined some

00:50:17.550 --> 00:50:20.460
of the very basics
of Islamic practice.

00:50:20.460 --> 00:50:23.030
This is how we wash our
hands before prayer,

00:50:23.030 --> 00:50:25.380
this is how we wash
our feet before prayer,

00:50:25.380 --> 00:50:28.810
these are the times
at which we pray.

00:50:28.810 --> 00:50:32.620
Unlike Omar ibn Said, who in
his dislocation from anyone

00:50:32.620 --> 00:50:36.440
who shared his faith, in that
dislocation he became open

00:50:36.440 --> 00:50:40.340
to conversion but Bilali
Muhammad, against all odds,

00:50:40.340 --> 00:50:43.300
seems to have been part
of a religious community.

00:50:43.300 --> 00:50:47.280
Not only were there other Muslims
on Sapelo Island who looked to him

00:50:47.280 --> 00:50:51.760
as their leader, he had 12
sons and seven daughters,

00:50:51.760 --> 00:50:54.280
all of whom were said
to pray by kneeling

00:50:54.280 --> 00:50:58.230
and bowing facing east
on woven mats.

00:50:58.230 --> 00:51:00.950
It may have been for
those 19 children

00:51:00.950 --> 00:51:04.150
that he wrote these
instructions and a further note

00:51:04.150 --> 00:51:06.880
about these instructions,
scholars who work

00:51:06.880 --> 00:51:12.620 position:56%
with the document today suggest
that the way he uses language speaks

00:51:12.620 --> 00:51:15.690
of a person who is in the process
of forgetting, who is fighting

00:51:15.690 --> 00:51:18.420
against that forgetting by
writing what he can remember.

00:51:18.420 --> 00:51:24.790
There are short excerpts from known
texts, there are repeated lines,

00:51:24.790 --> 00:51:26.740 position:56%
and he's trying to get down on paper

00:51:26.740 --> 00:51:28.730
for the following generations
everything he could

00:51:28.730 --> 00:51:30.740
possibly remember.

00:51:30.740 --> 00:51:35.020
Yet, despite these best efforts
to pass along his traditions,

00:51:35.020 --> 00:51:40.690
Islam did not long endure there
or anywhere else and a clue

00:51:40.690 --> 00:51:44.780
to what happened can be found in
the words of a missionary traveling

00:51:44.780 --> 00:51:48.480
through the south to preach on
slave plantations in the middle

00:51:48.480 --> 00:51:52.790
of the 19th century, a missionary
named Charles Colcock Jones.

00:51:52.790 --> 00:51:56.290
"Many Muhammed and Africans"
he noted, "had found ways

00:51:56.290 --> 00:51:59.350
to (his word) accommodate Islam

00:51:59.350 --> 00:52:03.250
to the new beliefs
being imposed upon them.

00:52:03.250 --> 00:52:07.690
God say they is Allah and
Jesus Christ is Muhammed.

00:52:07.690 --> 00:52:09.440
The religion is the same

00:52:09.440 --> 00:52:13.090
but different countries
have different names."

00:52:13.090 --> 00:52:17.010 position:56%
Now, this missionary considered this
to be evidence of Muslims inability

00:52:17.010 --> 00:52:21.630
to recognize the importance of
religious truths but in fact,

00:52:21.630 --> 00:52:25.020
it seems to prove exactly
the opposite.

00:52:25.020 --> 00:52:27.740
They understood that their
faith was important enough

00:52:27.740 --> 00:52:31.380
that they should listen for it
everywhere, even in a country

00:52:31.380 --> 00:52:34.590
so distant from the places where
they had once heard the call

00:52:34.590 --> 00:52:38.430
to prayer, even in a nation
where only non-Muslins

00:52:38.430 --> 00:52:42.040
like Thomas Jefferson
were able to own a Koran.

00:52:42.040 --> 00:52:46.720
I mentioned at the outset that
this mostly forgotten dimension

00:52:46.720 --> 00:52:49.810
of American religious
diversity changed dramatically

00:52:49.810 --> 00:52:52.950
around the year 1860.

00:52:52.950 --> 00:52:55.660
One reason for this is simply time.

00:52:55.660 --> 00:52:58.130
Omar ibn Said and Bilali Muhammed,

00:52:58.130 --> 00:53:01.270
the two of the four figures
I mentioned who remained

00:53:01.270 --> 00:53:04.920
in this country, they
both died around 1860.

00:53:04.920 --> 00:53:09.110
A number of dates has been
given for the death of each,

00:53:09.110 --> 00:53:12.870
some before the war and some
after but it's clear that neither

00:53:12.870 --> 00:53:16.120
