00:54:13.240 --> 00:54:18.490
Yet, the important thing to
remember is that the disappearance

00:54:18.490 --> 00:54:21.600
of religious traditions
doesn't always mean the end

00:54:21.600 --> 00:54:23.490
of their influence.

00:54:23.490 --> 00:54:27.520
We can hear echoes of early
American Islam in fact

00:54:27.520 --> 00:54:30.450
in early American Christianity
and even today,

00:54:30.450 --> 00:54:35.610 position:56%
and even in our broader culture,
particularly in musical styles borne

00:54:35.610 --> 00:54:40.470 position:56%
of the ritual known as the ring
shout, the primary ritual experience

00:54:40.470 --> 00:54:44.440
of early African-American
religious observants,

00:54:44.440 --> 00:54:50.020
which bears some resemblance to
Muslim ceremonies and is thought

00:54:50.020 --> 00:54:53.690 position:56%
by some scholars to have contributed
not just to the common style

00:54:53.690 --> 00:54:57.400
of worship but to the
blues and to jazz.

00:54:57.400 --> 00:55:02.170
Now, in conclusion, I'd like to
say that I focused on Islam here

00:55:02.170 --> 00:55:05.700
because it provides a real stark
example of the way religious

00:55:05.700 --> 00:55:08.230
and cultural practices
can be forgotten even

00:55:08.230 --> 00:55:12.700
if they were once common knowledge
but we could tell similar stories

00:55:12.700 --> 00:55:20.670 position:56%
of many other traditions and I like
to think that like those 6,487 books

00:55:20.670 --> 00:55:25.280
that were planted here, that have
grown into a library of millions,

00:55:25.280 --> 00:55:29.180
we should believe and we should
remember that all the beliefs

00:55:29.180 --> 00:55:33.830
of our past, even those
that have been forgotten,

00:55:33.830 --> 00:55:36.230
they're part of our common history.

00:55:36.230 --> 00:55:38.030
Thank you.

00:55:38.030 --> 00:55:48.800
[ Applause ]

00:55:48.800 --> 00:55:51.400
&gt;&gt; Well, it's a joy to be back
here at the Library of Congress

00:55:51.400 --> 00:55:55.260
and the Kluge Center and to
learn from Ted, and from Sally,

00:55:55.260 --> 00:55:57.700
and from Peter in these
wonderful lectures.

00:55:57.700 --> 00:56:00.850
I was instructed to give
some informal remarks

00:56:00.850 --> 00:56:04.330
and I guess my distinguished
colleagues heard the same

00:56:04.330 --> 00:56:07.690
instruction but, as good scholars,
they have given formal papers.

00:56:07.690 --> 00:56:12.040
I have come with my bumpkin tuba
solo to talk with you a little bit

00:56:12.040 --> 00:56:17.190
about the period 1940 to
1947, which is the period

00:56:17.190 --> 00:56:20.940
in which the United States
Supreme Court created the modern

00:56:20.940 --> 00:56:24.650
constitutional law of religious
freedom on the strength

00:56:24.650 --> 00:56:28.500
of the first amendment and its
guarantees of no establishment

00:56:28.500 --> 00:56:33.590
of religion and no prohibition
on its free exercise.

00:56:33.590 --> 00:56:40.530
Before 1940, between 1791 and
1940, only 23 cases arising

00:56:40.530 --> 00:56:44.180
under the first amendment religion
clauses reached the United States

00:56:44.180 --> 00:56:46.220
Supreme Court and in not one

00:56:46.220 --> 00:56:50.390
of those cases did the court
find an establishment of religion

00:56:50.390 --> 00:56:53.850
or a violation of free
exercise rights.

00:56:53.850 --> 00:57:01.130
After 1940, 183 Supreme Court cases
were heard on the religion clauses

00:57:01.130 --> 00:57:05.110
of the first amendment and
attendant statutory protections

00:57:05.110 --> 00:57:09.930 position:56%
of religious freedom, more than half
of which were findings of violations

00:57:09.930 --> 00:57:14.220
of either the establishment clause
or the free exercise clause.

00:57:14.220 --> 00:57:19.610
Clearly, something changed
dramatically in the 1940s and I'd

00:57:19.610 --> 00:57:22.170
like to use a couple
of minutes informally

00:57:22.170 --> 00:57:28.560
to explore a bit what changed,
why it changed, how it changed,

00:57:28.560 --> 00:57:33.590
and then what the significance of
that is for us in the 21st century.

00:57:33.590 --> 00:57:38.920
So, three main changes occur in
this period from 1940 and the case

00:57:38.920 --> 00:57:43.980
of Cantwell versus Connecticut to
1947, and the Supreme Court case

00:57:43.980 --> 00:57:47.380
of Everson versus Board
of Education.

00:57:47.380 --> 00:57:50.830
The first change is that the
Supreme Court, for the first time,

00:57:50.830 --> 00:57:55.660
applied the first amendment
religion clauses directly to state

00:57:55.660 --> 00:58:01.640
and local governments and created
a uniform and universal law

00:58:01.640 --> 00:58:06.280
of religious freedom
enforceable by the federal courts.

00:58:06.280 --> 00:58:11.630
Secondly, the Supreme Court read
the establishment clause guarantee

00:58:11.630 --> 00:58:15.870
and the free exercise
clause guarantee rigorously

00:58:15.870 --> 00:58:21.100
and attached rather substantial
scrutiny to the actions of federal,

00:58:21.100 --> 00:58:24.020
state, and local government
when they were challenged

00:58:24.020 --> 00:58:28.240
under either the establishment
clause or the free exercise clause

00:58:28.240 --> 00:58:30.680
and that scrutiny gave rise to wins

00:58:30.680 --> 00:58:35.820
and those wins encouraged ever more
litigation in the federal courts.

00:58:35.820 --> 00:58:37.580 position:56%
And the third thing that happened is

00:58:37.580 --> 00:58:42.580
that the Supreme Court proved
itself unusually solicitous

00:58:42.580 --> 00:58:49.360 position:56%
to marginal groups, highly unpopular
religious groups like Witnesses,

00:58:49.360 --> 00:58:53.550
and Adventists, and pacifists,
and atheists and others,

00:58:53.550 --> 00:58:57.150
who had not fared well
at all in state courts

00:58:57.150 --> 00:59:02.000
or in state legislatures and found
very little recourse and protection

00:59:02.000 --> 00:59:04.650
from the US Congress as well.

00:59:04.650 --> 00:59:08.530
Three major changes
and it's not accidental

00:59:08.530 --> 00:59:14.460 position:56%
that these changes occurred in the
1940s as we move toward the creation

00:59:14.460 --> 00:59:17.330
of a universal national law

00:59:17.330 --> 00:59:21.450
of religious freedom
enforceable by the federal courts.

00:59:21.450 --> 00:59:25.880
In the first place, we are
moving toward a national project

00:59:25.880 --> 00:59:27.900
in the mid-20th century.

00:59:27.900 --> 00:59:32.450
Already in the 1930s during the
Great Depression, as Congress

00:59:32.450 --> 00:59:36.980
and eventually the United States
Supreme Court after 1937 moved

00:59:36.980 --> 00:59:42.110
to try to create a national law on
many questions of health, safety,

00:59:42.110 --> 00:59:46.530
welfare, and even morality, even
in the face of countervailing state

00:59:46.530 --> 00:59:49.160
and local governmental concerns.

00:59:49.160 --> 00:59:52.310
World War II and the
budding Cold War underscored

00:59:52.310 --> 00:59:56.800
that national consolidation
project even more as Congress

00:59:56.800 --> 01:00:00.630
and the White House and the
Supreme Court together took leads

01:00:00.630 --> 01:00:05.900
in reaching national consolidation
on the fundamentals that needed

01:00:05.900 --> 01:00:08.400
to be enforced even in the face

01:00:08.400 --> 01:00:12.630
of countervailing state
and local interests.

01:00:12.630 --> 01:00:14.780
But most importantly to our project

01:00:14.780 --> 01:00:20.530
of religious freedom was the
1940s discovery in horror

01:00:20.530 --> 01:00:27.170 position:56%
of Hitler's death camps and Stalin's
gulags, where all sense of humanity

01:00:27.170 --> 01:00:30.630
and dignity had been
betrayed and a recognition

01:00:30.630 --> 01:00:34.510
that local bigotry run amuck
and unchecked can yield

01:00:34.510 --> 01:00:39.590
that massive barbaric treatment
of a particular religious

01:00:39.590 --> 01:00:43.790
and cultural people, in particular
the Jews, but not only the Jews,

01:00:43.790 --> 01:00:46.640
gypsies and many others as well.

01:00:46.640 --> 01:00:50.400
And in response, the
United States of America

01:00:50.400 --> 01:00:53.680
and the international
collection of states

01:00:53.680 --> 01:00:57.170
in the universal declaration
seized anew on the idea

01:00:57.170 --> 01:01:02.440
of religious freedom as a
universal good, a fundamental right

01:01:02.440 --> 01:01:05.590
to be enjoyed by every
person, by every people,

01:01:05.590 --> 01:01:07.930
in all contexts around the world.

01:01:07.930 --> 01:01:12.080
It became one of the greater four
freedoms that Roosevelt lifted up

01:01:12.080 --> 01:01:17.340
and it was considered essential to
the organization of a good society

01:01:17.340 --> 01:01:20.900
and a democratic policy to
have universal protection

01:01:20.900 --> 01:01:25.830
of religious freedom for all,
especially for minorities,

01:01:25.830 --> 01:01:29.660
especially for those that were
unpopular, especially for those

01:01:29.660 --> 01:01:33.910
that held religious views that
had been locally vilified.

01:01:33.910 --> 01:01:38.580
It was critical that especially
the outsiders felt welcome

01:01:38.580 --> 01:01:42.610
and had the constitutional
protection of the first amendment

01:01:42.610 --> 01:01:45.790
that they could call upon
in the federal courts

01:01:45.790 --> 01:01:48.080
and it was especially
considered important

01:01:48.080 --> 01:01:52.550 position:56%
that a person could be guaranteed
the protection of the federal courts

01:01:52.550 --> 01:01:57.830
under the first amendment
regardless of where she/he lived

01:01:57.830 --> 01:02:04.790
and therein lay the rub,
because we run four square

01:02:04.790 --> 01:02:08.410
into the constitutional
protection of federalism,

01:02:08.410 --> 01:02:11.580
built into the US Constitution
itself as you know,

01:02:11.580 --> 01:02:15.170
with its division of enumerated
powers amongst the federal

01:02:15.170 --> 01:02:19.760
government but also the guarantee
of reserved powers to the states,

01:02:19.760 --> 01:02:23.040
guaranteed in the 10th amendment,
guaranteed in Article IV,

01:02:23.040 --> 01:02:26.170
and jealously maintained
in the century

01:02:26.170 --> 01:02:32.170
and a half between 1791 to 1940.

01:02:32.170 --> 01:02:36.130
But furthermore, the first
amendment itself was problematic

01:02:36.130 --> 01:02:40.470
in this regard because
it singles out Congress.

01:02:40.470 --> 01:02:45.460
It says Congress shall make no
law respecting an establishment

01:02:45.460 --> 01:02:48.970
of religion or prohibiting
the free exercise thereof.

01:02:48.970 --> 01:02:51.280
It says nothing about the states.

01:02:51.280 --> 01:02:54.250
It's not even in the
passive voice like the second

01:02:54.250 --> 01:02:56.420
through ninth amendments
where we talk

01:02:56.420 --> 01:02:59.380
about there should be no
illegal searches and seizures

01:02:59.380 --> 01:03:03.300
or no unjust taking of property
which could be read generically

01:03:03.300 --> 01:03:06.030
to apply to any government,
federal or state.

01:03:06.030 --> 01:03:09.680
Here, the Congress was singled
out by the first amendment,

01:03:09.680 --> 01:03:13.640
Congress shall make no law
violating religious freedom.

01:03:13.640 --> 01:03:16.230
And whatever the intention
of the drafters

01:03:16.230 --> 01:03:21.010
of first amendment religion
clauses in 1789 happened to be,

01:03:21.010 --> 01:03:24.390
or the ratifiers in
1791 happened to be,

01:03:24.390 --> 01:03:27.680
that language was taken
universally to mean

01:03:27.680 --> 01:03:31.630
that the first amendment religious
freedom guarantees applied only

01:03:31.630 --> 01:03:35.840
to Congress and the federal
government leaving the then 48

01:03:35.840 --> 01:03:41.360 position:56%
individual states to govern religion
and religious freedom in accordance

01:03:41.360 --> 01:03:44.330
with their own local
state constitutions.

01:03:44.330 --> 01:03:48.630
Some states were generous in their
protections of religious freedom

01:03:48.630 --> 01:03:53.240
but many states maintained forms
of religious establishment,

01:03:53.240 --> 01:03:57.980
preferencing particular forms of
faith, putting in place policies

01:03:57.980 --> 01:04:03.950 position:56%
that enacted by coercion certain
forms of religious identity, belief,

01:04:03.950 --> 01:04:08.000
and practice and at the same
time put in place a number

01:04:08.000 --> 01:04:09.650
of encumbrances and abridgements

01:04:09.650 --> 01:04:13.560
and sometimes deeply
prejudicial actions towards

01:04:13.560 --> 01:04:15.470
religious minorities.

01:04:15.470 --> 01:04:20.750
So here was the problem, how
to create a universal law

01:04:20.750 --> 01:04:24.700
of religious freedom when the
text of the Constitution itself

01:04:24.700 --> 01:04:26.890
and the very federalist structure

01:04:26.890 --> 01:04:30.900
of the Constitution
seemed to stand in the way.

01:04:30.900 --> 01:04:34.360
And to accomplish that end,
the United States Supreme Court

01:04:34.360 --> 01:04:38.700
in this fateful set of
cases from 1940 to 1947,

01:04:38.700 --> 01:04:41.710 position:56%
performed a constitutional magic act

01:04:41.710 --> 01:04:46.450
that we lawyers call due
process incorporation.

01:04:46.450 --> 01:04:50.610
This will be technical for
30 seconds, check your email.

01:04:50.610 --> 01:04:55.490
The court looked to the 14th
amendment, passed in the aftermath

01:04:55.490 --> 01:04:59.200
of the Civil War, ratified in 1868,

01:04:59.200 --> 01:05:04.690
which has as its first guarantee
no state shall deprive any person

01:05:04.690 --> 01:05:09.690
of life, liberty or property
without due process of law.

01:05:09.690 --> 01:05:11.610
We call that the due process clause

01:05:11.610 --> 01:05:15.510
and the courts said
interpreting this term liberty,

01:05:15.510 --> 01:05:18.930
what is part of the
body, the corpus?

01:05:18.930 --> 01:05:22.490
What is incorporated
into the idea of liberty?

01:05:22.490 --> 01:05:25.720
Well, the first place we
will go is to look elsewhere

01:05:25.720 --> 01:05:28.670
in the constitutional
text in the Bill of Rights

01:05:28.670 --> 01:05:32.300
and other rights provisions set
out in the instrument as a whole

01:05:32.300 --> 01:05:36.540
and among other things, there was
a guarantee in the 14th amendment

01:05:36.540 --> 01:05:40.770
of religious liberty, and what
does religious liberty entail?

01:05:40.770 --> 01:05:44.560
Religious liberty entails
no establishment of religion

01:05:44.560 --> 01:05:49.590
and no prohibition on the
free exercise of religion

01:05:49.590 --> 01:05:53.830
and that little poof you
just heard is the completion

01:05:53.830 --> 01:05:57.700
of the constitutional
magic act because suddenly,

01:05:57.700 --> 01:06:02.830
what is read as Congress shall make
no law in effect becomes government

01:06:02.830 --> 01:06:04.730
of any sort, federal, state,

01:06:04.730 --> 01:06:08.850
and local government shall make
no law establishing religion

01:06:08.850 --> 01:06:11.900
or prohibiting the
free exercise thereof.

01:06:11.900 --> 01:06:16.460 position:56%
The first amendment applies directly
to Congress and by extension,

01:06:16.460 --> 01:06:18.970
other branches of the
federal government.

01:06:18.970 --> 01:06:21.380
The first amendment
applies indirectly

01:06:21.380 --> 01:06:24.900
through the 14th amendment
due process clause to state

01:06:24.900 --> 01:06:27.010
and to local governments alike.

01:06:27.010 --> 01:06:30.970 position:56%
You can stop checking your email and
now we can get back to the story.

01:06:30.970 --> 01:06:32.760
Why is this important?

01:06:32.760 --> 01:06:37.750
All of a sudden not only have we
structurally changed the first

01:06:37.750 --> 01:06:41.870
amendment so that it becomes
the universal law that seemed

01:06:41.870 --> 01:06:47.080
to be necessary in the 1940s in
the face of local bigotry run amuck

01:06:47.080 --> 01:06:52.830
in a highly civilized nation like
Germany, but we also now have

01:06:52.830 --> 01:06:56.080
through rigorous interpretation
of those two guarantees,

01:06:56.080 --> 01:07:00.590 position:56%
invited the federal courts into the
conversation about religious freedom

01:07:00.590 --> 01:07:05.080
in a way that had never taken place
in the prior century and a half

01:07:05.080 --> 01:07:09.540
of the republic and
unfurling in the 1940s forward

01:07:09.540 --> 01:07:14.550
for the next half century was the
rigorous law of no establishment

01:07:14.550 --> 01:07:18.030
of religion, separation of
church and state being one

01:07:18.030 --> 01:07:22.310
of the organizing axioms as the
Supreme Court addressed questions

01:07:22.310 --> 01:07:26.480
of religious teachers, and texts,
and ceremonies, and Bible readings,

01:07:26.480 --> 01:07:30.390
and symbols in public schools,
striking virtually all of them

01:07:30.390 --> 01:07:35.820 position:56%
