01:57:11.830 --> 01:57:17.190 position:56%
and more concerned that if they did
not embrace a more negative attitude

01:57:17.190 --> 01:57:19.890
towards slavery they would
lose the rest of their people.

01:57:19.890 --> 01:57:25.490
I mean, tens of thousands of
just Methodists in just New York

01:57:25.490 --> 01:57:29.810
so I think it's worth thinking
about the ways that Peter's point

01:57:29.810 --> 01:57:36.680
about a massive shift in attitude
may be expressed in disaffiliation

01:57:36.680 --> 01:57:41.170
and yet itself be deeply
religiously motivated.

01:57:41.170 --> 01:57:45.530
And then, the only other thing
I wanted to say before learning

01:57:45.530 --> 01:57:49.970
from John is that I've also
been so interested by the fact

01:57:49.970 --> 01:57:55.410
that the first really common
non-government corporations

01:57:55.410 --> 01:57:58.670
in American history were
religious corporations.

01:57:58.670 --> 01:58:04.340
Those are the first, the first
general incorporation statute was

01:58:04.340 --> 01:58:09.520
written in 1784, for religious
organizations and so one

01:58:09.520 --> 01:58:12.490
of the things to think
about is the longstanding

01:58:12.490 --> 01:58:16.150
and very deep relationship
between corporate status

01:58:16.150 --> 01:58:20.790 position:56%
and all kinds of religious entities.

01:58:20.790 --> 01:58:23.670
You can't hold property securely

01:58:23.670 --> 01:58:26.500
as a religious organization
unless you incorporate

01:58:26.500 --> 01:58:29.890
and that's been true
for more than 200 years.

01:58:29.890 --> 01:58:32.140
It's really interesting
how deep that goes.

01:58:32.140 --> 01:58:35.580
&gt;&gt; Let me just speak
to your question

01:58:35.580 --> 01:58:39.190
about the role of religious
ceremony.

01:58:39.190 --> 01:58:41.600
I'll start with an anecdote.

01:58:41.600 --> 01:58:45.140
Right in the middle of the heyday
of strict separation of church

01:58:45.140 --> 01:58:46.980
and state, there was
a poster that appeared

01:58:46.980 --> 01:58:51.460
in a California public
school and the poster read,

01:58:51.460 --> 01:58:56.080
"In the event of a nuclear attack,
the prohibition against prayer

01:58:56.080 --> 01:58:59.080
in public schools will be
temporarily suspended."

01:59:00.460 --> 01:59:03.260
[Laughter] And it speaks to
a question about the role

01:59:03.260 --> 01:59:08.340 position:56%
of religious ceremony and authentic
religious ceremony in some instances

01:59:08.340 --> 01:59:11.920
in times of crisis and
need and the recognition

01:59:11.920 --> 01:59:16.220
that when 9/11 occurs we go
to the National Cathedral

01:59:16.220 --> 01:59:18.920
and hear religious
officials pray and discourse

01:59:18.920 --> 01:59:20.870
about some of the fundamentals.

01:59:20.870 --> 01:59:25.300
In times of real Force Majeure,
there is new cooperation

01:59:25.300 --> 01:59:30.320
between religious and
political officials in seeking

01:59:30.320 --> 01:59:32.740
to alleviate those
that have suffered.

01:59:32.740 --> 01:59:35.440
In times of great crisis like
the Civil Rights Movement

01:59:35.440 --> 01:59:38.820
when we're seeking to bring
our African-American friends

01:59:38.820 --> 01:59:42.370
into full communion in
America, politicians

01:59:42.370 --> 01:59:47.780 position:56%
and clerics link arms walking
towards the achievement of some good

01:59:47.780 --> 01:59:49.470
and I think there's
some power in that,

01:59:49.470 --> 01:59:52.560
that Robert Bellah calls
the power of civil religion

01:59:52.560 --> 01:59:54.180
or what Emil Durkheim way back

01:59:54.180 --> 02:00:00.040 position:56%
when called the necessary
religious elements of communal life.

02:00:00.040 --> 02:00:03.380
And I think the Supreme
Court in fits and starts

02:00:03.380 --> 02:00:05.660
over the last 40 years
has come to realize

02:00:05.660 --> 02:00:10.450
that the establishment clause
really can't rise to or descend

02:00:10.450 --> 02:00:16.040
to intrusion on or reinvestigation
of those kinds of forms

02:00:16.040 --> 02:00:19.590
of what the court calls ceremonial
deism, that there is a place

02:00:19.590 --> 02:00:20.890
for some of this [inaudible]

02:00:20.890 --> 02:00:24.930
and that the establishment clause
isn't designed to second guess

02:00:24.930 --> 02:00:29.850
or third guess that nor to
give an individual dissenter

02:00:29.850 --> 02:00:34.490
from that religious expression
a kind of heckler's veto

02:00:34.490 --> 02:00:40.060
that would stymy the expression of
those forms of religious ceremony,

02:00:40.060 --> 02:00:45.010
sometimes authentic and rich and
textured in their expression.

02:00:45.010 --> 02:00:48.370
I happen to find that a
congenial read and I happen

02:00:48.370 --> 02:00:52.730
to think Bellah got this right
and I think it speaks to ideas

02:00:52.730 --> 02:00:56.800
that Benjamin Franklin had way
back when in his first discussions

02:00:56.800 --> 02:01:00.440
of public religion with a
CK on public by the way,

02:01:00.440 --> 02:01:04.420
when he's thinking through about
the necessity of having some kind

02:01:04.420 --> 02:01:07.650
of common belief, some
kind of common values

02:01:07.650 --> 02:01:12.130
which sit atop the particular
sectarian expressions of values

02:01:12.130 --> 02:01:14.820
and the corporations that
gather around it in worship

02:01:14.820 --> 02:01:16.660
and property holding and more.

02:01:16.660 --> 02:01:24.170
And, as Chief Justice Burger said
in the case of Lynch v Donnelly,

02:01:24.170 --> 02:01:28.430
it's far too late in the day to
impose such a crabbed reading

02:01:28.430 --> 02:01:31.020
of the establishment clause that
would allow the Supreme Court

02:01:31.020 --> 02:01:33.340
to unearth those practices.

02:01:33.340 --> 02:01:37.290
I think on that one,
the chief got it right.

